unicode.value: When carrying out laboratory procedures, a variety of glassware can be used. Determining the appropriate type of glassware to use relies on an understanding of the accuracy and precision required for the experiment, and then knowing which glassware best fits these needs. By determining the density of a liquid using various glassware types and comparing the average and standard deviations of the densities determined, the relative accuracy and precision of a graduated cylinder, volumetric pipette, and burette will be determined. Additionally, different methods of determining the density, both from replicate measurements and from graphical analysis, will be explored.

This page is dedicated to the CHE 131 students at DePaul University.

Please contact your instructor for any content related questions.
Experiment 1. Determining the Density of a Liquid â–¹ Interactive

1. Measure the volume of an object by observing the amount of fluid it displaces or can displace.
  2. Provide evidence and reasoning for how objects of similar:
    1. mass can have differing volume.
    2. volume can have differing mass.
  3. Identify the unknown materials by calculating density using displacement of fluid techniques and reference tables provided in the simulation.

When carrying out laboratory procedures, a variety of glassware can be used. Determining the appropriate type of glassware to use relies on an understanding of the accuracy and precision required for the experiment, and then knowing which glassware best fits these needs. By determining the density of a liquid using various glassware types and comparing the average and standard deviations of the densities determined, the relative accuracy and precision of a graduated cylinder, volumetric pipette, and burette will be determined. Additionally, different methods of determining the density, both from replicate measurements and from graphical analysis, will be explored.
